Headline::::
What can match the eccentrics of the funfair?




DateTime::::2016-02-16T17:56:35+0000



<p><span class="drop-cap"><span class="drop-cap__inner">I</span></span> went to the 812th annual <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.edp24.co.uk/news/oyez_oyez_the_mart_given_traditional_opening_in_king_s_lynn_1_4418069" title="">Kings Lynn</a> Mart on Monday, a sentence it makes me disproportionately happy to type. There we all were, gathered at noon on a bright, freezing February day in the marketplace listening to councillor Elizabeth Nockolds read out the proclamation that first granted its right to be held there in 1204. Our smartphones aloft to capture the moment, we huddled down inside our hollowfibre-filled jackets against the wind and were effortlessly connected back to the time of King John.</p>

<p>There is something ineffably comforting about the weight of history at your back. The Kings Lynn Mart was originally one of two trading fairs but evolved over time into a funfair – the first in the showmen’s calendar and a time to dust off old favourites and try out new inventions before the onslaught of the summer season. Perhaps this tradition explains why the greatest fairground engineer of the Victorian era (and therefore any other age) also emerged in Kings Lynn. <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.klmagazine.co.uk/2012/02/frederick-savage-genius-of-fun/" title="">Frederick Savage</a> applied his previous experience of developing and improving farm equipment to the invention of increasingly fantastic steam-driven rides, especially carousels.</p>

<p>Savage is basically the man behind everything we think of when we think of fairgrounds. He made the curlicued horses on his Platform Gallopers rock as well as circle, thanks to a series of eccentrics (the wheels mounted on revolving shafts to change rotation into back-and-forth motion, not a crowd of weirdos brought in from West Dereham for a day’s hard labour) under the carousel floor. The galloping horses were followed by racing peacocks, jumping cats and flying pigs, and then he gave the switchback to the world. Eight baroque gondolas, dragons edged in gilt, and simulacra of the new motorcars began to appear on the road powering round an undulating track. Imagine the glory.</p>

<p>Everything is electric at the modern Mart, of course. The lights are brighter, the music louder – but some of the glory remains. It is faded but, like the heavily worn gilt on the older rides, it is there. It is impossible to be cynical at the fairground. The very fact that it is not perfect – that you can see the joins, the nuts, the bolts, the hard graft holding it all together, – makes it real. Modern disaffection falls away. It is still impossibly exciting to spin round on a horse or sit on a golden dragon. It could be, in all important ways, 800 years ago again.</p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/jan/21/dont-give-a-damn-lucy-mangan-notebook">Let ‘em know you don’t give a damn – it’s very therapeutic | Lucy Mangan</a> </p>

<p>I have a new phone and it has been as dreadful a learning curve as you would expect. The thing that baffled me most has been the smallest. On the side of the magic box is the switch that turns it to silent. If you flick it one way, a red patch appears as a warning. The other, it does not. It has taken me weeks to realise that the red patch does not, as I assumed, warn you that your phone’s ringtone is on, rather that it is off.</p>

<p>I have never felt so out of my time. Of course, the danger is that you do not hear your phone, not that you accidentally disturb others and are crushed by the embarrassment. Of course. I am remembering a time as ancient as that of the first Mart. If you need me, I shall be in the tavern by the market place, watching the world wag past and wondering where all the monkeys and barrel organs went.</p>

<p>In view of all this, it should come as no surprise that I am delighted to hear <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/feb/15/lords-overruled-recording-laws-vellum-goat-calf-skin" title="">that vellum is likely to be reprieved</a>. We are still to inscribe our laws on goat and calf skin as we have done for 1,000 years instead of, as proposed, moving to archival paper <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/feb/10/uk-to-stop-printing-laws-on-vellum-to-save-80000-a-year" title="">to save £80,000 a year</a>. I cannot explain my delight, except to say that, like a fairground’s continuance down the ages, the survival of our ancient documents is a comfort. I wouldn’t like to deny either to generations yet to come.</p>




